Unmodified recording except for clipping narration at end. About 400 Sturnus vulgaris perched in trees at edge of dump singing/calling. Although a few of this species have been in town over the winter, today, the warmest day we've had in weeks (35 degrees F) and sunny, flocks of starlings are singing in tree tops all over town. Most flocks have been of 10 or fewer birds. This flock is huge. Little movement among the individual birds, just a few that have flown short distances within the flock. Undisturbed by a juvenile Bald Eagle that flew nearby (chased by crows) and an immature Red-tailed Hawk that flew to their small grove of trees and landed on a branch lower than the starling flock. Probably both sexes in the flock, but cannot confirm.

recordings.rmk:
Starlings sing in their breeding area around their nisting boxes. One of them  sings 4 phrases:
artspecific whistle at the beginning, then a long second phase (until 00:30) with a mix of individuel whistles, rattling (Rätschen"), blathering ("Schwätzen") etc.,  and a lot of imitations: in 00:07 Vanellus vanellus, in 00:16 alarm call of Erithacus rubecula and so on.  Phase 3: shorter and lower with cracking (knackenden) and chattering (ratternden) sounds. Phase 4: shrill screeching (Kreischen) with wings flattering.  From  00:46 in the foreground  a Starling, which prefers  a very special rhythm motive, only song in this summer period. I am always fascinated of the artspecfic and different individual whistlings of  Starlings! Same Starlings and situation as in XC696691

recordings.type: call, imitation, song, aggressive calls, mimicry/imitation

recordings.rmk: Starlings sing in their breeding area around their nisting boxes. One of them prefers a very special rhythm motive (beginning in 00:03). Another often repeats a three- or foursyllabic motive - may be the modificied song of Poecile montana (first in 00:09). In 01:57 imitation of Falco tinninculus, in  03:14 of Buteo buteo etc. etc . I am very fascinated of the artspecfic and different individual or imitated whistlings of Starlings! Same place and birds as in XC696692

    • mimickry, Arctic Tern, Sterna paradisaea, call, iii-rr, at 0:36.2

recordings.rmk:
Very interesting: 5, 4, then 6 , at least 3 Starlings sit together in the sun on the little roof of a nisting box , and two or three sing together with a lot of typical imitations. They like best to imitate the Northern Lapwing, the Red Kite and the Eurasian Golden Oriole - both, his raugh call and his whistling song, even in variation. 
Young Starlings in the nisting box are to hear at the end of the recording..
Other nisting boxes around.
Imitations from: 
Eurasian Blackcap (00:07, 01:11, 01:22); Northern Lapwing: 00:15;  00:34 Oriole, followed from Common Buzzard;  00:44 Northern Lapwing, Red Kite, Northern Lapwing;  Black Kite (01:14);  Red Kite (01:28); Northern Lapwing (01:36); Common Cuckoo (01:37);  Oriole (01:45);  2:00 electronic ringing ??, followed from Black Kite's call, transformed into Red Kite's call;  Oriole (02:12); Red Kite (02:23); Oriole (02:32); Common Cuckoo (2:37);  from 02:41 a serie of Oriole whistlings (variations) and calls; Barn Swallow; Kestrel (03:04); Oriole (03:20); Red Kite (03:42); Northern Lapwing (3:55);  04:03: Red Kite, followed from Northern Lapwing, Red Kite, begging young Starlings inside the n.box

Starling sit in a dense overgrown tree - this function as a night and day roost and resting point for the local breeding starlings (typical 30-40 a day - occasionally up to 400). So many 'weird' calls are heard from here - and good number of imitation - some years they favor bee-eaters, some years waders or a song bird (icterine warbler, wood warbler) or human devices mobile phone – a truck reversing.But one thing is certain and that is they are fast learners - a bee-eater passes by and a minute later they have it in there song - sometimes for days - which is 'frustrating'.

The unbelievably protean utterances of a Common Starling. I missed the first part of the song, with excellent imitations of Black-capped Chickadee and Great Horned Owl. In this cut, you can hear imitations of Swainson's  Hawk, Red-tailed Hawk, Sora, Solitary Sandpiper, RIng-billed Gull, Northern Flicker, American Robin, and others.
